revision.text:
The [[2009 World Series of Poker]] was the 40th annual [[World Series of Poker]] (WSOP). Held in [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas]] at the [[Rio All Suite Hotel and Casino]], the 2009 series began on May 27 and featured 57 [[poker]] championships in [[List of poker variants|several variants]]. All events but the $10,000 World Championship No Limit [[Texas hold 'em]] Main Event, the most prestigious of the WSOP events, ended by July 15. The final table of the Main Event, known as the [[November Nine]], was suspended until November, to allow for better television coverage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldseriesofpoker.com/news/article.asp?newsID=1855 |title=2008 World Series of Poker Set for May 30 through July 15 in Las Vegas |publisher=WorldSeriesofPoker.com |accessdate=2008-09-15| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080916221056/http://www.worldseriesofpoker.com/news/article.asp?newsID=1855| archivedate= 16 September 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>  Following the WSOP custom since 1976, each of the event winners received a [[World Series of Poker bracelet|championship bracelet]] in addition to that event's prize money, which this year ranged from US$87,778 for the $500 Casino Employees No-Limit Hold'em  to US$8,546,435 for the Main Event.

==WSOP game variants==
Most of the tournaments played at the WSOP are variants of [[Texas Hold 'em]].  Hold 'em is a [[community card]] game where each player may use any combination of the five community cards and the player's own two [[glossary of poker terms#hole|hole cards]] to make a poker hand, in contrast to [[poker variants]] such as [[stud poker|stud]] or [[draw poker|draw]] in which each player holds a separate individual hand.  Between 2000 and 2009, hold'em surpassed [[seven-card stud]] as the most common game in U.S. casinos.<ref name="15stud">{{cite web| url=http://www.twoplustwo.com/magazine/issue21/clark0906.html| title=The Dying Days of Las Vegas 1-5 Stud| accessdate=October 4, 2006| last=Clark | first=Bryan|date=September 2006 | work=Two Plus Two Internet Magazine | publisher=Two Plus Two Publishing | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061123021244/http://www.twoplustwo.com/magazine/issue21/clark0906.html  | archivedate = 2006-11-23}}</ref>  Seven-card stud is a poker variant wherein each player is dealt two hole cards and one face-up to start the hand, followed by three more face-up cards one at a time, and then another hidden card, with betting after each round. Another poker variant played is [[Omaha hold 'em|Omaha]], a game in which each player is dealt four hole cards and must use exactly two of them in conjunction with three community cards to make the best possible five-card hand.  Other games played at the 2008 tournament included [[Razz (poker)|Razz]], [[HORSE]], and Deuce-to-Seven.

Within each of these poker variants a myriad of options exist.  For example, depending on the betting structure, a tournament might be described as [[glossary of poker terms#no-limit|no limit]], [[glossary of poker terms#limit|limit]] or [[glossary of poker terms#pot-limit|pot-limit]]. Games may also include other variations on the rules governing the execution of the specific game such as [[glossary of poker terms#shootout|shootout]], [[Glossary of poker terms#E|eight or better]], or [[Glossary of poker terms#H|heads up.]]

==2009 highlights==
There were 57 events, two more [[2008 World Series of Poker results|than in 2008]].  The main event had 6,494 buy-ins, 350 fewer than the previous year. Other changes for 2009 include the elimination of [[Buying in (poker)|rebuy events]] and the introduction of triple starting chips.<ref>[http://pokerworks.com/poker-news/2009/03/16/2009-wsop-rule-and-structure-changes.html Expect Rule and Structure Changes at 2009 WSOP], a March 16, 2009 article from pokerworks.com. Accessed 2009-07-29.  [https://www.webcitation.org/5jdtN0bP5?url=http://pokerworks.com/poker-news/2009/03/16/2009-wsop-rule-and-structure-changes.html Archived] 2009-09-08.</ref>

In recognition that 2009 was the 40th WSOP, the tournament started with a special $40,000 No-Limit event.  As one of the most expensive poker tournaments ever, the event attracted what considered to be one of the toughest poker fields ever assembled.<ref name ="top10">{{cite web|url=http://www.cardplayer.com/poker-news/7126-2009-wsop-the-10-best-performances-of-the-summer|title=2009 WSOP—The 10 Best Performances of the Summer|last=Murphy|first=Stephen|date=2009-07-03|accessdate=2009-07-08|publisher=''Cardplayer Magazine''}}</ref>  Poker pro, [[Vitaly Lunkin]], won his second bracelet in this event.  Lunkin then finished in second place at the $10,000 pot-limit Omaha event and the $50,000 HORSE Championship, finishing the summer with over $2.7 million.<ref name = "top10" />  [[David Bach (poker player)|David Bach]], a player with several final table appearances, won his first bracelet in the $50,000 HORSE Championship.  At 18 hours and 44 minutes the final table of the $50K HORSE event was the second longest final table in WSOP history.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}

[[Jeff Lisandro]] became the fifth player to ever win three bracelets in the same year, and the first ever to win bracelets in all three stud variants offered at the WSOP (stud high-only, stud high-low, and Razz) in the same year. Poker superstar [[Barry Greenstein]], said that "A lot of people might have said before this year, we may not ever see another guy win three bracelets because the fields are so big... Lisandro proved them wrong."<ref name = "top10" />  He was the first player to do so since Phil Ivey did it in 2002.  By winning two bracelets, Ivey, considered by many to be the best overall poker player in the world,<ref name = "top10" /> became the youngest player to ever amass seven WSOP bracelets. The milestone means he is tied with [[Poker Hall of Fame]]r [[Billy Baxter (poker player)|Billy Baxter]] at sixth place on the [[World Series of Poker multiple bracelet winners|most bracelets list]].

Due to capacity limitations, the 2009 WSOP turned away over 500 players from the Main Event.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}}  [[Patrik Antonius]], [[T. J. Cloutier]], [[Layne Flack]], [[Ted Forrest]], [[Brandon Adams (poker player)|Brandon Adams]], [[Richard Ashby]], and [[Mickey Appleman]] were among the notable players turned away from the Main Event.  [[1996 World Series of Poker|1996 WSOP]] champion [[Huck Seed]] would have been included in that list, if he had not won the [[National Heads-Up Poker Championship]] which meant he was guaranteed entry into the 2009 WSOP Main Event.<ref name = "soldout">{{cite web|url=http://www.cardplayer.com/poker-news/7145-hundreds-turned-away-from-the-wsop-main-event|title=Hundreds Turned Away from the WSOP Main Event| last=Murphy| first=Stephen| date=2009-07-06| accessdate=2009-07-08| publisher=''Cardplayer Magazine''}}</ref>

Another tournament which met its capacity limits was the "$1,000 buy-in Stimulus Special." This event set a new record for a non-main event tournament with 6,012 participants.<ref name="early records">{{cite web|url=http://www.pokernewsdaily.com/wsop-1000-stimulus-special-tournament-sold-out-2670/ |title=WSOP $1,000 Stimulus Special Tournament Sold Out |last=Jenkins |first=Tom |date=2009-05-30 |accessdate=2009-05-31 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5jdtKzGbd?url=http://www.pokernewsdaily.com/wsop-1000-stimulus-special-tournament-sold-out-2670/ |archivedate=2009-09-08 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref><ref name="PocketFives">{{cite web|url=http://www.pocketfives.com/online-poker-scene/numerous-records-shattered-at-2009-wsop-4324639 |title=Numerous Records Shattered at 2009 WSOP |work=PocketFives |publisher=PocketFives |date=2009-05-31 |accessdate=2009-05-31 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5jdtKB6Mp?url=http://www.pocketfives.com/online-poker-scene/numerous-records-shattered-at-2009-wsop-4324639 |archivedate=2009-09-08 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>

