'''Elisabeth Volkenrath''' (née Mühlau; 5 September 1919 – 13 December 1945) was a German supervisor at several [[Nazi concentration camps]] during [[World War II]].

Volkenrath, née Mühlau, was an ''ungelernte Hilfskraft'' (unskilled worker) when she volunteered for service in a concentration camp. She started in October 1941 at [[Ravensbrück concentration camp]] as a simple ''[[Aufseherin]]''. In March 1942, she went to [[Auschwitz Birkenau]] where she worked in the same function as at Ravensbrück. At Auschwitz, she met ''SS-Rottenführer'' Heinz Volkenrath, who had worked there since 1941 as ''SS-Blockführer''. They married in 1943. Elisabeth Volkenrath participated in the selection of prisoners for the gas chambers and in November 1944 was promoted to ''Oberaufseherin'' for all camp sections for female prisoners at Auschwitz.<ref name="New Exhibition Guide">{{cite book|last=Knoch|first=Habbo (ed)|title=Bergen-Belsen: Wehrmacht POW Camp 1940–1945, Concentration Camp 1943–1945, Displaced Persons Camp 1945–1950. Catalogue of the permanent exhibition|publisher=Wallstein|place=Göttingen|year=2010|isbn=978-3-8353-0794-0}}</ref>{{rp|218}}

Elisabeth Volkenrath was transferred to [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp|Bergen-Belsen]] when Auschwitz was closed. From February 1945, she was ''Oberaufseherin'' (supervising wardress) at Bergen-Belsen.<ref name="New Exhibition Guide"/>{{rp|218}}

==Belsen trial==
In April 1945, she was arrested by the [[British Army]], and stood trial in the [[Belsen Trial]]. Found guilty, she was [[death sentence|sentenced to death]], and executed by hanging at [[Hamelin]] prison by [[Albert Pierrepoint]] on 13 December 1945.<ref name="New Exhibition Guide"/>{{rp|218}}

